# DOM Day 5 - Forms and Form Submission

## Topics Learned
- HTML Forms
- Form Submission
- submit Event
- preventDefault()
- Reading User Input
- Displaying Submitted Data

---

## What is a Form?

A form is used to collect data from users.

Examples:
- Login Form
- Registration Form
- Contact Form
- Medical Report Form

---

## Basic Form Example

```html
<form id="myForm">

    <input
        type="text"
        id="cityInput"
        placeholder="Enter City"
    >

    <button>
        Submit
    </button>

</form>

<h2 id="result"></h2>
```

---

## submit Event

The `submit` event runs when a form is submitted.

```javascript
form.addEventListener("submit", function(event) {

});
```

---

## preventDefault()

```javascript
event.preventDefault();
```

Stops the browser from reloading the page after form submission.

Without `preventDefault()`:
```text
Submit Form
↓
Page Reloads
```

With `preventDefault()`:
```text
Submit Form
↓
JavaScript Handles Data
↓
No Reload
```

---

## Reading User Input

```javascript
let city =
document.querySelector("#cityInput").value;
```

`.value` gets the data entered by the user.

Example:

```text
Input Box:
Pune
```

Result:

```javascript
city = "Pune";
```

---

## Displaying Data

```javascript
document.querySelector("#result").innerText =
city;
```

Displays the submitted city on the webpage.

---

## Complete Example

```javascript
let form = document.querySelector("#myForm");

form.addEventListener("submit", function(event) {

    event.preventDefault();

    let city =
    document.querySelector("#cityInput").value;

    document.querySelector("#result").innerText =
    city;

});
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- Forms collect user data.
- submit event handles form submission.
- preventDefault() stops page reload.
- .value reads user input.
- innerText displays data on the page.

